<li id="cite_note-Krishanvii-26">^ <a href="#cite_ref-Krishanvii_26-0" title=""><sup><i><b>a</b></i></sup></a> <a href="#cite_ref-Krishanvii_26-1" title=""><sup><i><b>b</b></i></sup></a> For Krishan's views on Ganesha's dual nature see his quote: "<span lang="sa-Latn" title="International Alphabet of Sanskrit Transliteration" class="Unicode" style="white-space:normal; text-decoration: none" xml:lang="sa-Latn">Gaṇeśa</span> has a dual nature; as Vināyaka, as a <i><span lang="sa-Latn" title="International Alphabet of Sanskrit Transliteration" class="Unicode" style="white-space:normal; text-decoration: none" xml:lang="sa-Latn">grāmadevatā</span></i>, he is <i><span lang="sa-Latn" title="International Alphabet of Sanskrit Transliteration" class="Unicode" style="white-space:normal; text-decoration: none" xml:lang="sa-Latn">vighnakartā</span></i>, and as <span lang="sa-Latn" title="International Alphabet of Sanskrit Transliteration" class="Unicode" style="white-space:normal; text-decoration: none" xml:lang="sa-Latn">Gaṇeśa</span> he is <i><span lang="sa-Latn" title="International Alphabet of Sanskrit Transliteration" class="Unicode" style="white-space:normal; text-decoration: none" xml:lang="sa-Latn">vighnahartā</span></i>, a <i><span lang="sa-Latn" title="International Alphabet of Sanskrit Transliteration" class="Unicode" style="white-space:normal; text-decoration: none" xml:lang="sa-Latn">paurāṇic devatā</span></i>." Krishan, p. viii.</li>
